Introduction

Epstein-Barr Virus (EBV) is a herpes virus and the cause of mononucleosis. Like other herpes viruses, infected cells can remain in a latent phase in the infected person their entire lives. B-cells are the usual target of EBV. When infected, B-cells can become immortalized, and can be cultured in vitro as Lymphoblastoid Cell Lines (LCLs). Like some other viruses, this immortalization can predispose the individual to certain types of cancer. For instance, Hodgkins Lymphoma is derived from EBV-infected B cells.

Today, were going to look at gene expression data to see how EBV infection changes the transcriptome. We will be looking at B-cell and LCL RNA-seq data from 5 donors, where LCLs were made from each of the donors B-cells. Please start from this file and add code/code blocks/and commentary as needed.

Why do we log-transform gene expression data? ###Because the original RPKM data have very large variance, some values are very large, this would cause the small values to be hard to see, thus we can not see the distribution clearly. Log-transform would reduce this variance while keep the difference between each values, and we can see the distribution clearly.

Why do we use RPKM+1? ###Because some values are 0, this would cause error when doing log transform, and RPKM+1 would finally result in 0, which is equal to the original one. Indeed, most of the RPKM values are larger than 1, values lower than 1 is not as such important.

EdgeR is exceptionally versatile, with many different options for analysis. Today, youre going to use the GLM-quasi-likelihood approach to calculate differential expression. Below is some incomplete code that you can use to start with. Please complete the code so that edgeR uses your countMatrix to calculate differential expression comparing B cells to LCLs. ###get the group information
ct=as.factor(gsub("([A-Z]+)_[ABCDE]","\\1",colnames(countMatrix)))
###produce DGElist
res= DGEList(counts=countMatrix, group=ct)
###since different samples have different coverage, so we need calculate the normalization factor
res = calcNormFactors(res)
###then get the design matrix
design = model.matrix(~ct)
###dispersion estimation
res= estimateDisp(res,design)
###perform quasi-likelihood F-tests
fit= glmQLFit(res,design)
qlf = glmQLFTest(fit, coef=2)
###get all differential status of genes
allDEStats_unpaired = as.data.frame(topTags(qlf,n=nrow(countMatrix)))
allDEStats_unpaired$Gene.ID=row.names(allDEStats_unpaired)

donor<-as.factor(gsub("([A-Z]+)_([ABCDE])","\\2",colnames(countMatrix)))

Question 4b (3.5 pts)

Another way to ensure that P-values are well-behaved is to make a Q-Q plot. A Q-Q plot, in this case, will show the expected P-values (under the null hypothesis) on the x axis, and actual p-values on the y-axis. Recall that by the definition of a P-value, if you generate n p-values under the null hypothesis, you expect to see 1 p-value of 1/n or lower, two of 2/n or lower, etc. Here, n is the number of DE tests you performed. Make a Q-Q plot of p-values for your DE analysis. Use -log(P) for both axes (this puts the most significant in the upper right, and least significant in the lower left). Also include the line y=x in red for comparison. For a well-behaved statistical test, most of the points should lie along the y=x line.

Do most of the P-values lie along the y=x line?

No, most of the pvalues are above the y=x line.

What does this mean about how we did our analysis? What would you do differently if we were to redo the analysis?

Since the expected pvalues and actual pvalues are not in line, we can decide that our pvalues are biased to certain parts of our data. We may need to redo analysis and more accurately consider assumptions made during analysis.

Question 5a (2 pts)

GOrilla, which we use below, can take a single ranked list as input. Here, you should make two ranked lists of gene IDs, one with the gene IDs sorted by log FC from high to low, and the other from low to high. Use the paired analysis for this question. You will only want gene IDs written to the file (e.g.no row or column names, no quotes) - GOrilla will give error messages if it is not properly formatted.

lowtohigh <- allDEStats_paired[order(allDEStats_paired$logFC), ]
hightolow <- allDEStats_paired[order(allDEStats_paired$logFC,decreasing=TRUE), ]
genelowtohigh <- lowtohigh$Gene.ID
genehightolow <- hightolow$Gene.ID
writeLines(genelowtohigh, con = "lowtohigh.txt")
writeLines(genehightolow, con = "hightolow.txt")

Question 5b (6 pts)

Now use GOrilla to measure gene set enrichment analysis for both sets of genes. http://cbl-gorilla.cs.technion.ac.il/

Use Homo sapiens; a single ranked list of genes (those we just created - run it twice, once per file); and all ontologies.

When inspecting the results, consider both the significance of the enrichment, the degree of enrichment, and the number of genes involved. For instance, a high-fold enrichment for a very specific term can give more insight than a more significant but lower fold enrichment for a more generic term. Alternatively, enrichments involving fewer genes are more likely to occur by chance, and so may have a high fold enrichment, but nonetheless be spurious.
